[3] British Columbia
Date: Wed 7 Jun 2017 2:17 PM PDT
Source: The Similkameen Spotlight [edited]
http://www.similkameenspotlight.com/local-news/warning-issued-for-princeton-families-interior-health/


An increase in the number of cases of pertussis, also known as whooping cough, is being seen in the Princeton area [British Columbia]. Interior Health would like to remind the public about the importance of making sure your immunizations are up to date.

The pertussis vaccine is part of the routine childhood vaccinations that are given at 2 months, 4 months, 6 months, and 18 months old, and again at age 4 to 6 years (before kindergarten). A pertussis vaccine is also given to teens at 14 to 16 years of age (grade 9) in British Columbia. The vaccine is safe and effective and parents are advised to check their child's immunization record to make sure they are up to date. It is especially important that infants receive the first dose of pertussis vaccine on time and without delay to protect them from serious pertussis complications.

Information about accessing immunization records can be found at ImmunizeBC (http://www.immunizebc.ca. To discuss pertussis immunization for children or to book an appointment, contact your local public health centre. Adults who have never been immunized for pertussis can contact their local health centre to inquire about getting the vaccine.

[Byline: Andrea Demeer]

